<br>
at any point in the future you can -exercise- the option : <br>
-&gt; poney up the money to buy the actual share from your employer at the price of the offer (and get taxed on the interest)<br>
<br>
-&gt; sell the share and pocket the difference of the current market value minus the value at the time of the offer (and get taxed on the gain). obviously, if the option is worth less, you lose money. <br>
<br>
this gives employees a fairly good incentive to work their ass off to increase the value of the options they are offered. <br>
<br>
S.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=trainwreckjm>Trainwreck jm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 187<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/18/03 11:02:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=625.topic&index=54>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: US War Crimes?</span><hr size=1> The situations Wenin mentioned most certainly do occur. Especially during the tech/dot.com boom, it was not at all unusual for people to end up with tax liabilities greater than the value of their shares. <br>
<br>
At the time a Non-qualified option is exercised, any gain realized above the grant price is taxed not as Capital Gains, but as Regular Income. You will probably owe state and social security taxes on the amount as well. But if you hold onto the stock after exercising the option, any additional gain above the price at which you excercised is then taxed at the lower capital gains rate. The point being, there is a definite tax advantage to exercising &amp; holding over just waiting til you are ready to cash out before you exercise.<br>
<br>
So if an employee is holding vested (meaning, exercisable) options that expire in 5 years, and he feels optimistic about the company's prospects (which one hopes an employee might think of his company), it is to his benefit, tax-wise, to exercise the option then hold the stock, rather than sit on the option for however long.<br>
<br>
But if the stock then suddenly plummets to below the grant price - as happened with so many companies in the past couple of years - you still owe the income taxes on the difference between the grant price and the price at which you exercised the option, even though you never actually had the money in your hands. When dealing with companies that skyrocketed - then plummeted - as quickly as tech's and teleco's did, the financial hit can be considerable.<br>
<br>
Now some might say &quot;tough shit. if they were smart they would sell all the stock right away&quot;. Well, 'tough shit' maybe, but the second part is just silly. While some people might use their options gains to pay the grocery bill or take a vaction, other people use the money for long-term investment purposes (just like with all other kinds of income). There is nothing intrinsically foolish about holding onto stock in one's own company, especially one that has already shown you a nice return.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>this gives employees a fairly good incentive to work their ass off to increase the value of the options they are offered. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is the ostensible reason that companies like Microsoft, Cisco, etc.. grant options to all their employees, but it has little basis in reality. Stock options are granted because, unlike regular payroll, they do not have to be listed on the balance sheet as an expense.  They also reap huge tax savings for the issuing companies ($2 billion for Microsoft in 2000, for example).<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=makino>Makino</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Flowers Before Boys</span><br>  Posts: 237<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/19/03 1:39:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=625.topic&index=55>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://roforums.dhs.org/phpBB/images/avatars/gallery/Avatars/mage-female.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: US War Crimes?</span><hr size=1> Again you are assuming you have exercised the options.  The vast majority of the people who worked during the dotcom era did not exercise their options.  The reason being the offer price when they signed on was locked anyways and if their options had vested, there was no real advantage for them to exercise their stocks unless they felt that it was at the highest point and wanted to cash them out.  Most people figured out that options aren't taxable until you exercise them.  This is why I say the situation that Wenin described wouldn't really happen.  <br>
<br>
To illustrate, I'll use some RL examples.  I have several friends and contacts throughout the high tech sector.   One friend works for Yahoo, and was employee number 65.  This means he was granted a lot of stock options and at a low offering price point.  His net worth was several million dollars, but all of that was tied up in non exercised stock options.  After the dot bomb, his net worth was crap.  But he did not have to pay taxes on his previous net worth in stock options because he never exercised them.  Oh, this is also a classic example of the reasons why you should diversify your portfolio.<br>
<br>
Another friend of mine worked for Amazon.com.  Unlike the friend that worked at Yahoo, this guy did exercise his vested options.  Unfortunately, and despite my advice, he took the gains he made ($60k or so) and blew it all on toys and the finer pleasures of life.  He figured he could just cash out more options to pay for the taxes at the end of the year.  Too bad he was fired and was unable to vest more options.  He was then stuck with a huge tax bill at the end of the year.  Whereas my other friend at Amazon, he used a conservative approach to his options by not exercising a whole bunch, diversified his portfolio, in this case a house, and didn't have to pay a huge tax at the end of the year.  This guy still works at Amazon though.<br>
<br>
Also, I'm not 100% sure on this, but even if you exercise your options, you are not taxed on the overall value of your stocks, but any money you generated from them.  So dividends and the money you made from selling the options are taxed, but not the theoretical value of your stocks at any given time that remain unsold.  Realize that stock values are in constant flux, so just because you hold stocks worth one million dollars doesn't mean the next day it will be worth that much, or less or more than that even.  So at what point do you tax a person?  Another way to look at this is if you buy a house for $100k in San Jose,CA ten years ago.  During that time the house value rose to $800k.  Other than the property tax you are paying anyways, you aren't going to be dinged by the government to cough up the tax on the 700k you theoretically made from the house until you actually sell it.  What I am getting at is, investments and holdings aren't taxed until you see a return of liquid assets (money) out of it.<br>
<br>
And don't pipe up about estate tax, I think it's BS anyways ^_^<br>
<br>
Again, I'm not 100% sure, so corrections are more than welcome as it's always good to learn more about this stuff. <p>&lt;hr&gt;<br>
