 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=trainwreckjm>Trainwreck jm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 188<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/19/03 2:53:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=625.topic&index=58>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Again you are assuming you have exercised the options. The vast majority of the people who worked during the dotcom era did not exercise their options.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Makino, i'm not assuming anything. What Wenin alluded to, and what you said can't really happen, are real cases, not hypotheticals. It was widely reported on a couple of years ago, and i'm sure if you ask your contacts in the tech sector, they will have heard a lot about it. Here's one article i just found:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.thestandard.com/article/display/0,1151,21902,00.html">www.thestandard.com/artic...02,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
This is not about whether options are evil tax timebombs waiting to explode on anyone who holds them - of course they aren't - but rather its about whether some people can and did end up with tax bills larger than the value of the stock they held, having never pocketed a dime. It can happen, it does happen, and during the option-crazy dot.com-boom, when stocks rose and fell so precipitously, it became more common. Whether or not it is unjust is debatable (i don't really think it is).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also, I'm not 100% sure on this, but even if you exercise your options, you are not taxed on the overall value of your stocks, but any money you generated from them. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Right, i should have said that the capital gains tax will apply to any gain you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>realize</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> above the exercise price. you are not taxed on that until you sell. But you do have to pay income taxes on any gain over the grant price when you exercise.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...and if their options had vested, there was no real advantage for them to exercise their stocks unless they felt that it was at the highest point and wanted to cash them out<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, this is not necessarily true - especially not during a booming stockmarket. There can be very real, very substantial tax advantages to exercising your options if you think that the price will go higher. Any realized gains above the exercise price will be taxed as Capital Gains, not income. <br>
<br>
Say you have 1000 options at a grant price of $10 a share. They vest in 1 year, and expire in 5. After 1 year, the stock is at 20. You think the company's prospects are excellent and that the stock will continue to rise. Now lets say that your instincts are correct, and 5 years from now the stock is at 100. (if this example seems exaggerated, remember the era and companies we are discussing here <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
If you have held the options and exercise them now, your entire gain of $90,000 dollars will be taxed as income (you said you are paying 50% total). It will also be subject to state and SS taxes. This will leave you with a tax bill or $45,000.<br>
<br>
But if you had exercised the options at $20 and held the stock for 4 more years (just like you held your options), only that original gain of $10,000 would be taxed at 50% ($5,000), the remaining $80,000 - if you sell the shares, which you don't have to do - would be taxed at the 20% capital gains rate ($16,000). $5000 + $16,000 = total taxes of $21,000.<br>
<br>
Hold the options = $45,000 net gain<br>
Exercise options and hold the stock = $69,000 net gain<br>
<br>
This is not to say that this strategy is riskless, or that its the wisest course for all people in all situations. It merely illustrates that people can have valid motivation to exercise their options before they are ready to sell the stock.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=soprena>Soprena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 475<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/19/03 4:10:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=625.topic&index=59>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So if an employee is holding vested (meaning, exercisable) options that expire in 5 years, and he feels optimistic about the company's prospects (which one hopes an employee might think of his company), it is to his benefit, tax-wise, to exercise the option then hold the stock, rather than sit on the option for however long.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Relatively few have the cash to exercise the option and hold the stock. In high-tech companies, options often are given to employees all across the wage scale, from the president to the lowest-paid admins. and office services people. While it's theoretically possible to exercise the option and hold the shares, essentially no one does. <br>
<br>
And because the option is granted at the then-market price, exercising it immediatly is kind of silly. One could just go out and buy the shares on the open market.  The benefit options provide is a way to share in the growth of one's company's share value WITHOUT spending cash out-of-pocket. Another benefit is that there is no cash risk if the share price goes down.  <br>
<br>
Top execs. often exercise options and sell immediately when they need cash. This commonly occurs in April (federal income tax bills). Flipping options like this also is a nice way to pay a college bill, buy a new car, etc.  The benefit of this is that they do not need the cash up-front to buy the shares. The brokerage firm(s) that handle the company ISO plan will lend the employee the cash to exercise the option.<br>
<br>
Finally, for buying and holding shares, many companies offer ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) plans. The employees typically buy shares once per quarter at the lower of the price set at the plan entry date, or the then-current market value, minus a fixed percentage. In my company it's 15%. Some people flip those, earning a fast, free (except for taxes) 15% on their money, but I buy and hold those shares.<br>
